    <abstract>
      <para>
      Graphics recognition is a multi-disciplinary domain,
      involving techniques as heterogeneous as signal processing, image processing,
      pattern recognition, or computer vision. A research team working in the domain
      cannot start an application from scratch. It must be able to reuse whole or part
      of software implemented for previous work, as well as experience collected at
      these occasions. The working base built up in this way allows research projects
      to be efficiently conducted, by reusing existing material, standardizing program
      coding, and making ideas and software exchanges easier.
      </para>

      <para>
      For several years, the <ulink url="http://www.loria.fr/equipes/qgar/">Qgar Research Team</ulink> at 
      <ulink url="http://www.loria.fr">LORIA</ulink> has devoted much effort to the construction of such a 
      software environment 
      <ulink url="../../html/bibliography/bibliography.html">[Tombre et al, 1998]</ulink> 
      <ulink url="../../html/bibliography/bibliography.html">[Dosch et al, 2000]</ulink> 
      <ulink url="../../html/bibliography/bibliography.html">[Rendek et al, 2004a]</ulink>
      , including three main parts:
  
      <itemizedlist>
        <listitem>
          <simpara>
	  QgarLib is a library of C++ classes implementing basic graphics analysis and recognition methods.	  
	  </simpara>
	</listitem>

        <listitem>
          <simpara>
	  QgarApps is an applicative layer, including higher-level applications (binarization, edge detection, 
	  text-graphics separation, thick-thin separation, vectorization...). A third-party application, either 
	  designed apart from the Qgar software or not, can be integrated into the system by wrapping it with a 
	  predefined C++ class, without recompiling any part of the system itself <ulink url="../../html/bibliography/bibliography.html">[Rendek et al, 2004b]</ulink>.
	  </simpara>
	</listitem>

        <listitem>
          <simpara>
	  QgarGui is a graphical interface to design and run applications, provided with data manipulation and display capabilities.
	  </simpara>
	</listitem>

      </itemizedlist>

      This environmnet has been used within the frame of several projects, in particular DocMining, supported by the French national 
      program for software technologies <ulink url="../../html/bibliography/bibliography.html">[Clavier et al, 2004]</ulink>.
      </para>

